This movie is neither  extension of Queen nor about showing woman empowerment. This is a movie about a kleptomaniac and her journey who happens to be an American Indian. There is always a story in all our life whether u make it  bahubali of a story or a simple one like Simran. I don't understand why people are making this a debate on women empowerment. 

Also its a chicken and egg story. Movies are inspired from real lives at the same time movies do impact human lives and thought processes. So people who thinks this movie will make girls spoilt should understand that its first a reflection of what already exists in our society. 

The real deal is how the story unfolds and how Kangana and Hansal Mehta nails it once again because this one gonna be hit by word of mouth only.  I doubt people who have not visited US or who does not watch Hollywood would need time to understand the pulse of this movie and its setting in US. Because we are used to seeing how KJo or Chopra clan gives a larger than life impression of the NRI lives. While in reality its different and needs to be shown to Indian audience realistically.

The teaser of Kangana Ranaut's Bollywood movie Simran has apparently offered a hint that the movie may be a rip-off of French movie Amélie, which was released in 2001.

The teaser of Simran, which was released on YouTube on Sunday, has impressed fans and made them eagerly wait for its theatrical release. They liked the madness and natural acting of Kangana Ranaut and feel that she might get another National Award for this movie.

But some people feel that the background score featured in the teaser of Simran is a copy of a tune from Bollywood movie Barfi. And a few others say that the movie is a copy of French movie Amélie. This highlights that housekeeping duties are done by ethnic minority groups (Muslim, Asian, Indian, Black)
Are they sitting in a cafeteria of a Bank / Courthouse ?

In the next scene, her father questions her need for a house when she can stay with them and questions her sexual behaviour
Praful, who wants to get another house because she feels trapped, admits that she's sluttish.
(Indians consider women of free spirited nature as sluts.  Free Spirited Nature = Open Invitation for Sex)

Next Scene Praful is in Las Vegas (She's wearing a cap which says I LOVE LV)
This is probably a celebration of her getting a house but we don't see her housekeeping friends.
She is drunk and talking with the bartender and notices a hot guy who comes and sits at the bar.
She flirts with him using cliche pick up lines and the guy leaves.
The bartender tells her that the guy has gone to play BACCARAT (a card gambling game for resident Indians)
Praful in trying to proceed with the flirting ends up playing and winning at BACCARAT
Next, with the money she has won she's enjoying the Las Vegas life and buys an expensive dress.
This is probably where she gets addicted to the gambling


To gamble further, she needs money. She steals once and enjoys it.
She starts stealing with disguises.
She gets GAMBLING AND STEALING ADDICTION.
So Praful is NOT A KLEPTOMANIAC.
Kleptomaniacs don't steal because they need money or for personal benefit.

She admits of her addiction to the guy who is pursuing her and who doesn't take her seriously
(His name is Sameer. we don't know if he's an ex-husband or another suitor arranged by her parents or just a guy who likes her)

There are some more scenes of her disguises and a gambling scene where she is crying (looks fake but not sure)

The cops get hold of her and she tries to escape by hitting the cops.
There's a cat and mouse game with the cops.

Possibly next scenes are from Climax, where she is going to hit her Dad and realizes that she has gotten into a mess.
She goes to Sameer's house and probably confesses but he probably ditches her.

Whether she gets off scot-free or the cops put her in Jail, we don't know yet.
